annotation.TEXT: Oh, my god. Wow. That was a hilariously bad attempt to jump over those munchers. Granted, they're harder to avoid this way than if I was swimming, but come on. That was still not that tricky of a jump.
There's another of those coin shapes. This one almost looks like the letter "Y". And actually, looking back, that previous one sort of looked like an "X". Is that what they actually say? "X" and "Y"?
Zzzzwwwweeeeeeee!!!!
Heh. It's Kaizo Chuck made easy! (Even easier since I can cape-thwack him!)

Nice, now all that's left is a less-dangerous yellow shell (unless I idiotically hit myself with that shell somehow).
Heck, yeah! Hmm... If I can get just 4 more 50-star hits without having another sub-40 hit occur, my average will rise above 40! I wonder if I can pull that off...

Okay, he's gone for the moment. Now, one of the turn blocks above this "top hat" of fragile blocks should have something...
...Yeah, there's a current in the way, which is why you can't be swimming. (However, swimming might make it easier to collect the proper coins from that rectangle here if you wanted.)
Ah, since the shell-less yellow koopa just bit it, I most certainly can disable the disco by just swimming up a ways, then coming back down.
Nuts. It doesn't look like I can reach that Lava Lotus, so I can only dodge its attacks.
Also, my attempt to release my reserve flower back there so I could potentially grab it later was in vain. (Maybe if I had released it towards the left side of the level instead...)
Hello, and welcome back to Super Marina World! Now, before I get to the voting results, Kona informed me of a couple things that I did miss in 6-3...
Now, up here is a P-switch. Guess what it's gonna be used for? Oh, and you have to remain a runner the entire way while backtracking, in order to get through a couple of currents.
Bonk! Well, I was just hit by a pitch, so I can take first base now, right?

You can use these blocks to change whether you're swimming or not. Now here, you can't swim against the current, but you can run against it, so you've gotta turn off the underwater physics to get through.
There's the goal, but wait, wasn't this a red level? Where's the secret exit? ...Oh, ho, ho! What's this?
Got most of them, but I missed that star coin... No, wait. I didn't. Just like last time, I can just hit a nearby swimming block in order to reach it.

It may look at first like you'd need to be a swimmer to reach this power up, but runners can use the P-switch to take care of that problem, although that makes getting through the munchers to the left a little trickier.
Ooh! A hidden 1â™¥P! This is why I often like checking suspiciously empty-looking alcoves like this!
Also, yeah, I'll try coming up with a new tie-breaker room idea the next time there's a tie to break.
First of all, I missed the sharp, stabbing pain of Bony Beetle's bones... No, actually, I just simply screwed up there. Alright, die, all of you!
Whoa! Yeah, that current down there is strong!
Well, I can run and jump normally, and there are these note blocks at the start for some reason...
Oh, this last block's got something in it! (Also, it's a good thing it didn't break, or I would've had a hard time aiming for the top of the goal!)
Hey there, Chuck. How's it going?
Barf! How did I screw that up?
Oh, this part. Now, it's obvious that you're meant to trap the fish above the green blocks, but since I've got a shell... (*Insert evil laughter here*)
Doesn't look like I can fight this current, even with the turbo button. I wonder if there's a way to get up there...
I'm not sure if this wet area is a good place for pitching practice, but it's gotta be better than inside a volcano or a thundercloud!

Huh, that's weird. That initial brush up against the side of the water block here didn't trigger swimming mode. Oh, well. Whatever. I think it's neat that you can choose how you want to finish the level, and you can aim for the top of the goal either way.
M-M-M-M-MONSTER KILL!
Zwee!

Next, you have a choice. You can swim to avoid the munchers more easily, but this makes the cheepos a hazard. Or, you can turn off the water and the cheepos will be harmless, but avoiding the munchers will be a bit trickier. I'll choose the latter.
Yep, a flower. Alright, I'm outta here. (If any other turn blocks in this level contain an item that I missed, let me know!) Now, for those voting results...
Farfignewton. Yeah, that part's tricky. Maybe I should've chosen to swim here.
To be continued...

There's a current at the bottom that prevents swimmers from going through, so that means, we've gotta fall through this shaft without the watery effect. Hopefully, you have a cape, because otherwise, trying to dodge all of the coins will be really tricky. (And it's kind of tricky even with a cape!)
Goal tape average so far: 3164 / 80 = 39.55 stars each.
Well, it looks like I'm starting off swimming. Oh, but this is neat right here.

Now that I've already gotten the secret exit, I don't have to avoid these coins again.

DOUBLE KILL!
Hmm... I can run through this current, but that won't exactly help me. I've gotta swim, and to do that, I've gotta turn off these green blocks as well.

And this makes the path to the castle visible. Now, it's odd that I was initially able to go to the castle from 6-B beforehand. However, I think one of the previous version updates supposedly fixed that, though I wouldn't see the change here unless I started a brand new save file.
Alright, well, I guess I'll head on over to 6-B next, since that one came in second in the voting.
Gotta run through another current here, so turn off the swimming effect if it's active.
That's kind of neat how that Bouncing Chuck was set up there.
Alright, I think that's enough current fighting. It's pretty obvious that I'm probably never meant to get into the flooded top and bottom zones.
Oh, wow. Really? Talk about a pointless path. But, then again, the original SMW had some pointless paths, such as Chocolate Island 3's loop.
Goal tape average so far: 3074 / 78 = 39.410 stars each.
Now to use the P-switch to proceed through the level the normal way.
Alright, there are the half dozen levels that you guys can vote for, and like usual, your votes will determine where I go next time!
Now, for this next part, you want to avoid all of the coins. It's easier if you remain swimming, but...
Huh. It really looks like I'm standing on the middle current tile there. Is the middle current tile actually a solid block? If that's the case, then I'm probably not meant to ever get down there.
COINS! I'd better quickly switch to my cape for these.
Huh, are those coins forming a shape of a Japanese symbol or something? If so, what does it say?
Alright, 6-4 is next! So, let's check out this Leaky Tunnel...

I used a random number generator off screen (by entering "int rand7" into my TI-82) to determine that random level up there. However, unless the random level chosen was 9-6, it wouldn't have made a difference (9-6 would've caused a tie for 2nd place).
I don't think the status of the ON/OFF blocks matters, though, so don't worry about them. Now, at the bottom of this shaft where those five coins were dodged, activate the P-switch and climb up.

Alright, so this "reveals" the path to the warp star, as expected. However, I had already come in through the back door before, so this "reveal" is pointless now. Yay! Now, let's go back into 6-B for the normal exit...
Yeah, that current tile is definitely solid.
Goal tape average so far: 3204 / 81 = 39.556 stars each.
D'oh, I missed a star coin! Oh, wait. No I didn't. I can just activate swimming mode and go back for it!
Fortunately, I was successful.
Obviously, I can't fight that current. Gotta take the upper route.
Maybe I should've been ducking too! (I imagine that this is much easier if you swim!)
Now, over here, should I swim with the switch turned ON, or run and jump with the switch turned OFF? I'll go with the latter, but I think you could choose to do it either way.
Of course, I'll slow the footage down for certain things, such as me stupidly running into a Chuck...

You could either swim or run here. Swimming is easier, but runners can get this power up, which I could use. Also, no "cheating" the system. The current above cannot be backtracked through, not even by runners (so, you can't first get the power up and then decide to swim).
Nice, a 1â™¥P. Now, the middle turn block in the next setup should have an item as well...
Yes, it was totally necessary to slow it down like that while I was collecting that star coin.

Made it! Yeah, that was a really tricky and clever puzzle. Now, I had already seen raocow do this, but I probably would've eventually figured it out on my own after getting the normal exit first. Yeah, this path eventually leads to the secret exit.
Yeah, I actually can go down here, and this must be where the secret exit is!
There's another coin shape, which looks kind of like a "Z", so I guess these coin shapes said "X", "Y", and "Z". Do they mean anything important, though?
Then quickly race back to the location of that coin rectangle that you hopefully cut through like I mentioned earlier and climb up there.
Up here, cut a path through the coins like this, leaving some on the bottom and some on the top. This'll be important later.
Next up is a six-tile high jump. While technically possible to clear with a jump, it's much simpler to just swim over it.
I almost hit my head on the munchers up there. That would've been silly.

And there's that familiar star-shape, but it's made of turn blocks this time. Huh. Most of them were made of coins, but world 1's was made of brown blocks, and this one's made of turn blocks. Gotta check every turn block...
Alright, here I am again at the goal...
Okay, now over in this area, there are a couple of turn blocks that actually do contain items. However, I think I want to get rid of Magikoopa first...
Oh, yeah. In case you thought of just swimming up to the secret exit and not bothering with that puzzle...
That was awesome. Okay, now I assume the pipe above the midpoint is just the level's midpoint entrance.
To swim, or not to swim? That is some sort of question...
